    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Modern historians agree that the United Nations has been largely ineffective at preventing major interstate wars in the 21st century due to the limitations of its Security Council, which is often paralyzed by the need for unanimity among the P5 veto powers. While the UN succeeded in stabilizing some volatile regions through peacekeeping missions or facilitating diplomatic talks like the eventual Israel-Palestine peace process, these efforts are heavily dependent on the political will of member states, which varies significantly during times of leadership transitions. Consequently, many scholars view the current UN system as a vital framework for international diplomacy and humanitarian aid, but fundamentally incapable of unilaterally stopping large-scale armed conflicts without stronger enforcement mechanisms.",
